  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What are the best high-scoring Scrabble words ending in ED?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "QUIZZED (35 pts), JAZZED (32 pts), and FIZZED (28 pts) top the list. More commonly playable options include FOXED (16 pts), HEXED (16 pts), BOXED (15 pts), and MIXED (15 pts) — all using high-value tiles with the reliable -ED ending." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How does adding ED to existing words work in Scrabble?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Adding -ED to a verb already on the board is called hooking. If JUMP is on the board, you can extend it to JUMPED by adding ED at the end. You score the full word plus any new crosswords the E and D create. This works with most verbs — PLAY to PLAYED, FIX to FIXED, BOX to BOXED — making ED one of the most useful suffixes for board extensions." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Is it better to play ED words or hold tiles for a bingo?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "It depends on your rack. If holding E and D leaves you with strong bingo potential (like ING or TION combinations), keep them. But if your remaining tiles are unbalanced, play the ED word now. ED itself is only worth 3 points, so the extension value must justify holding. A 30+ point ED play is almost always better than speculating on a bingo." }
      }
    ]
  })} />

  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 pt-4 pb-12">
